  "answer": "The target does not concede that the Egyptian New Kingdom palatial economy was centrally redistributive in the same manner as the Hittite/Mycenaean systems. The forbidden case asserts an identity of redistributive structure, but the target's mechanism distinguishes between palace-based and temple-based redistribution as materially different institutional arrangements. Even if the Egyptian palace engaged in centralised collection and disbursement, the target specifies that Egypt's grain-storage was physically decentralised across the Nile valley and that the political economy relied on temple-based redistribution. Temples in Egypt constituted a durable, geographically distributed network of storage and authority that was not co-located with a single seismically vulnerable palatial administrative compound. The Hittite and Mycenaean systems concentrated storage, administrative records, and elite decision-making within palatial citadels whose physical destruction severed the redistributive chain. In Egypt, the temples provided an alternative institutional backbone that could maintain storage and redistribution functions even if a particular palace suffered damage, because the storage infrastructure and the loci of economic authority were not collapsed into a single seismically exposed node. The target therefore provides a specific process-based distinction—the spatial and institutional decoupling of storage and authority from the singular palatial centre—that holds under the counterfactual observation of a centrally redistributive Egyptian palace, because centralised redistribution does not entail physical centralisation of storage or institutional dependence on a single palatial compound."
